Here's the pattern using a custom `Window` subclass with `Preferences` for fast state persistence:

**1. Create a ViewModel for your note page:**

```csharp
// NoteViewModel.cs
public class NoteViewModel : INotifyPropertyChanged
{
    private string _draftText = string.Empty;
    public string DraftText
    {
        get => _draftText;
        set { _draftText = value; PropertyChanged?.Invoke(this, new(nameof(DraftText))); }
    }

    public event PropertyChangedEventHandler? PropertyChanged;
}
```

**2. Create a custom Window subclass that saves/restores state:**

```csharp
// AppWindow.cs
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    private readonly NoteViewModel _viewModel;

    public AppWindow(Page page, NoteViewModel viewModel) : base(page)
    {
        _viewModel = viewModel;
        // Restore any previously saved draft on launch
        _viewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", _viewModel.DraftText);
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        _viewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", _viewModel.DraftText);
    }
}
```

**3. Wire it up in `App.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    private readonly NoteViewModel _viewModel = new();

    public App() => InitializeComponent();

    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new NotePage(_viewModel), _viewModel);
}
```

**4. Bind in your note page:**

```xml
<!-- NotePage.xaml -->
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             x:Class="MyApp.NotePage">
    <Editor Text="{Binding DraftText}" Placeholder="Start typing..." />
</ContentPage>
```

```csharp
// NotePage.xaml.cs
public partial class NotePage : ContentPage
{
    public NotePage(NoteViewModel vm)
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        BindingContext = vm;
    }
}
```

### Key points

- **`OnStopped`** — fires when the app is fully backgrounded; save here.
- **`OnResumed`** — fires when returning from background; restore here.
- **`OnDestroying`** — also save here because Android's back button can skip `Stopped`.
- **`Preferences`** is ideal for small values like draft text — it's fast enough to avoid ANR timeouts on Android (~5s limit).
- **Don't save in `OnDeactivated`** — that fires for transient focus loss (notifications, split-screen) and the app may never actually background.
